<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-03-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-03-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="465" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d465">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 365.117/295</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                Ambassador <persName type="to">Penfield</persName>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-03-21">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 21, 1916</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1167. Your 1185, 14th. Will Ghiloni’s sworn statement be accepted? If
                            not, what guaranty will be required? Again mention that Department’s
                            records show clearly Ghiloni was impressed into Italian army and did not
                            volunteer. This Government endeavored obtain his release from Italian
                            army but without success.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>